{"title_page": "Haute Autorit\u00e9 pour la transparence de la vie publique", "text_new": "{{copy edit|date=March 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox government agency\n| name                = HAVP\n| full_name           = Haute Autorit\u00e9 pour la transparence de la vie publique\n| logo                = \n| formed              = {{Start date|2013|12|19}}\n| chief1_name          = Jean-Louis Nadal\n| type                = [[Governmental organization]]\n| website             = https://www.hatvp.fr/\n}}\n\nThe '''Haute Autorit\u00e9 pour la transparence de la vie publique''' ('''HATVP''') is a [[France|French]] administrative authority in charge of checking the patrimonial status and activities to detect potential [[conflict of interest|conflicts of interest]] of some French [[Civil service|public servants]].\n\n== History ==\nUntil 1988, preventing ethical problems in the [[Politics of France]] was based on [[Criminal procedure]] of crimes such as [[Conflict of interest]] or [[Cronyism]], but there was no means of preventing these kinds of problems.<ref>{{cite web\n| url=http://www.hatvp.fr/historique\n| archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20190814142515/http://www.hatvp.fr/historique\n| archive-date=2019-08-14\n| title=historique\n| publisher=hatvp.fr\n| accessdate=2019-12-15\n| url-status=dead\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 1988, the [[Luchaire Affair]] happened: between 1982 and 1986, while [[Charles Hernu]] was the French [[Minister of the Armed Forces (France)|Minister of Defence]], France supplied shells to [[Iran]]. This was allowed by a French commission because of a fake mentioning other countries rather than Iran. This affair was revealed by the ''Presse de la Manche'' newsparer, then by a report by the ''Contr\u00f4le g\u00e9n\u00e9ral des arm\u00e9es'' published by [[L'Express]] in January 1987.<ref>{{cite web\n| url=https://www.lexpress.fr/informations/1987-l-affaire-luchaire_603634.html\n| date=1995-03-30\n| title=1987: l'affaire Luchaire \n| publisher=[[L'Express]]\n| accessdate=2019-12-15}}</ref>\n\nAfter this [[Political scandal|scandal]], the first ''transparency of public life'' law was voted: it defined the state funding of political parties, and made it mandatory for some public servants to publish their financial status.<ref name=\"fnfo\">{{cite web\n| url=https://www.francetvinfo.fr/replay-radio/histoires-d-info/la-transparence-de-la-vie-politique-a-marche-forcee-1988-2014_1769191.html\n| date=2015-01-06\n| title=1987: La transparence de la vie politique \u00e0 marche forc\u00e9e\n| publisher=[[France Info]]\n| accessdate=2019-12-15}}</ref> However, this was still very incomplete.\n\nIn 1994, a parliamentary working group led by [[Philippe S\u00e9guin]] made 18 proposals including the limitation of election expenses and a reform of the status of political parties, and the extension of the mandatory declaration of status to more public servants.<ref name=\"fnfo\"/>\n\nOn April 10th 2013, after the [[Cahuzac affair]], the HAVP is created.<ref>{{cite web\n| url=https://www.lejdd.fr/Politique/Actualite/Transparence-une-Haute-autorite-pour-quoi-faire-601252\n| date=2013-04-10\n| archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.lejdd.fr%2FPolitique%2FActualite%2FTransparence-une-Haute-autorite-pour-quoi-faire-601252%23\n| archive-date=2014-10-27\n| title=1987: Transparence : une Haute autorit\u00e9, pour quoi faire?\n| publisher=[[Le Journal du Dimanche]]\n| accessdate=2019-12-15}}</ref>\n\n==Missions==\nThe main missions of the HATVP are:<ref>{{cite web\n| url=https://www.hatvp.fr/la-haute-autorite/#\n| title=La haute Autorit\u00e9\n| publisher=hatvp.fr\n| accessdate=2019-12-15}}</ref>\n* Preventing conflicts of interest for main public servants\n* Checking the evolution of the holding of public servants during their service\n* Checking wrong declarations from public servants\n* Controlling \"[[Revolving door (politics)|revolving door]]\" behaviors  between public service and private sector\n* Controlling [[Lobbying]]\n\n==Composition==\nThe HAVP is composed of:<ref>{{cite web\n| url=https://www.hatvp.fr/la-haute-autorite/linstitution/organisation/\n| title=Organisation\n| publisher=hatvp.fr\n| accessdate=2019-12-15}}</ref>\n* A president\n* Two members elected by the [[Conseil d'\u00c9tat (France)|Conseil d'\u00c9tat]]\n* Two members elected by the [[Court of Audit (France)|Court of Audit]]\n* One member nominated by the president of the [[National Assembly (France)|National Assembly]]\n* One member nominated by the president of the [[Senate (France)|Senate]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official|https://www.hatvp.fr/}}\n\n[[Category:Government of France]]\n", "text_old": "{{copy edit|date=March 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox government agency\n| name                = HAVP\n| full_name           = Haute Autorit\u00e9 pour la transparence de la vie publique\n| logo                = \n| formed              = {{Start date|2013|12|19}}\n| chief1_name          = Jean-Louis Nadal\n| type                = [[Governmental organization]]\n| website             = https://www.hatvp.fr/\n}}\n\nThe '''Haute Autorit\u00e9 pour la transparence de la vie publique''' ('''HATVP''') is a [[France|French]] administrative authority in charge of checking the patrimonial status and activities to detect potential [[conflict of interest|conflicts of interest]] of some French [[Civil service|public servants]].\n\n== History ==\nUntil 1988, preventing ethical problems in the [[Politics of France]] was based on [[Criminal procedure]] of crimes such as [[Conflict of interest]] or [[Cronyism]], but there was no means of preventing these kinds of problems.<ref>{{cite web\n| url=http://www.hatvp.fr/historique\n| archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20190814142515/http://www.hatvp.fr/historique\n| archive-date=2019-08-14\n| title=historique\n| publisher=hatvp.fr\n| accessdate=2019-12-15\n| url-status=dead\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 1988, the [[Luchaire Affair]] happened: between 1982 and 1986, while [[Charles Hernu]] was the French [[Minister of the Armed Forces (France)|Minister of Defence]], France supplied shells to [[Iran]]. This was allowed by a French commission because of a fake mentioning other countries rather than Iran. This affair was revealed by the ''Presse de la Manche'' newsparer, then by a report by the ''Contr\u00f4le g\u00e9n\u00e9ral des arm\u00e9es'' published by [[L'Express]] in January 1987.<ref>{{cite web\n| url=https://www.lexpress.fr/informations/1987-l-affaire-luchaire_603634.html\n| date=1995-03-30\n| title=1987: l'affaire Luchaire \n| publisher=[[L'Express]]\n| accessdate=2019-12-15}}</ref>\n\nAfter this [[Political scandal|scandal]], the first ''transparency of public life'' law was voted: it defined the state funding of political parties, and made mandatory for some public servants to publish their financial status.<ref name=\"fnfo\">{{cite web\n| url=https://www.francetvinfo.fr/replay-radio/histoires-d-info/la-transparence-de-la-vie-politique-a-marche-forcee-1988-2014_1769191.html\n| date=2015-01-06\n| title=1987: La transparence de la vie politique \u00e0 marche forc\u00e9e\n| publisher=[[France Info]]\n| accessdate=2019-12-15}}</ref> However, this was still very incomplete.\n\nIn 1994, a parliamentary working group led by [[Philippe S\u00e9guin]] makes 18 proposals including the limitation of election expenses and a reform of the status of political parties, and the extension of the mandatory declaration of status to more public servants.<ref name=\"fnfo\"/>\n\nIn 2013, after the [[Cahuzac affair]], the HAVP is created on 10 April 2013.<ref>{{cite web\n| url=https://www.lejdd.fr/Politique/Actualite/Transparence-une-Haute-autorite-pour-quoi-faire-601252\n| date=2013-04-10\n| archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.lejdd.fr%2FPolitique%2FActualite%2FTransparence-une-Haute-autorite-pour-quoi-faire-601252%23\n| archive-date=2014-10-27\n| title=1987: Transparence : une Haute autorit\u00e9, pour quoi faire?\n| publisher=[[Le Journal du Dimanche]]\n| accessdate=2019-12-15}}</ref>\n\n==Missions==\nThe main missions of the HATVP are:<ref>{{cite web\n| url=https://www.hatvp.fr/la-haute-autorite/#\n| title=La haute Autorit\u00e9\n| publisher=hatvp.fr\n| accessdate=2019-12-15}}</ref>\n* Preventing conflicts of interest for main public servants\n* Checking the evolution of the holding of public servants during their service\n* Checking wrong declarations from public servants\n* Controlling \"[[Revolving door (politics)|revolving door]]\" behaviors  between public service and private sector\n* Controlling [[Lobbying]]\n\n==Composition==\nThe HAVP is composed of:<ref>{{cite web\n| url=https://www.hatvp.fr/la-haute-autorite/linstitution/organisation/\n| title=Organisation\n| publisher=hatvp.fr\n| accessdate=2019-12-15}}</ref>\n* A president\n* Two members elected by the [[Conseil d'\u00c9tat (France)|Conseil d'\u00c9tat]]\n* Two members elected by the [[Court of Audit (France)|Court of Audit]]\n* One member nominated by the president of the [[National Assembly (France)|National Assembly]]\n* One member nominated by the president of the [[Senate (France)|Senate]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official|https://www.hatvp.fr/}}\n\n[[Category:Government of France]]\n", "name_user": "WikiUser134583", "label": "safe", "comment": "Grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haute_Autorit%C3%A9_pour_la_transparence_de_la_vie_publique"}
